member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to
member.summary: "q1 decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) < magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale."
member.remarks: This relation is used to determine the 'directionality' of relative qualities such as 'decreased strength', relative to the parent type, 'strength'.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.different_in_magnitude_relative_to
member.summary: "q1 different_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) NOT =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale."

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.directly_associated_with
member.summary: "q1 directly_associated_with q2 iff q1 is dependent on q2, and the magnitude of q1 increases if the magnitude of q2 is increased, or the magnitude of q1 decreases if the magnitude of q2 is decreased. The relationship is not necessarily linear."
member.remarks: Example: 'Lewy bodies increased number related to dystrophic neurite increased number' (from annotation of PMID:8740227 in http://ccdb.ucsd.edu/1.0/NDPO.owl#ndpo_404). Here the increase in the number of lewy bodies is directly_associated_with the increase in the number of dystrophic neurites.\nAssociation is weaker than correlation or proportionality. These relations may be later added to PATO.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.has_cross_section
member.summary: "s3 has_cross_section s3 if and only if : there exists some 2d plane that intersects the bearer of s3, and the impression of s3 upon that plane has shape quality s2."
member.remarks: Example: a spherical object has the quality of being spherical, and the spherical quality has_cross_section round.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.has_part
member.summary: "Q1 has_part Q2 if and only if: every instance of Q1 is a quality_of an entity that has_quality some Q2."
member.remarks: We use the has_part relation to relate complex qualities to more primitive ones. A complex quality is a collection of qualities. The complex quality cannot exist without the sub-qualities. For example, the quality 'swollen' necessarily comes with the qualities of 'protruding' and 'increased size'.

member.summary: "q1 increased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) > magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale."
member.remarks: This relation is used to determine the 'directionality' of relative qualities such as 'increased strength', relative to the parent type, 'strength'.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.inversely_associated_with
member.summary: "q1 inversely_associated_with q2 iff q1 is dependent on q2, and the magnitude of q1 decreases if the magnitude of q2 is increased, or the magnitude of q1 increases if the magnitude of q2 is decreased. The relationship is not necessarily linear."
member.remarks: Association is weaker than correlation or proportionality. These relations may be later added to PATO.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.reciprocal_of
member.summary: "q1 reciprocal_of q2 if and only if : q1 and q2 are relational qualities and a phenotype e q1 e2 mutually implies a phenotype e2 q2 e."
member.remarks: There are frequently two ways to state the same thing: we can say 'spermatocyte lacks asters' or 'asters absent from spermatocyte'. In this case the quality is 'lacking all parts of type' - it is a (relational) quality of the spermatocyte, and it is with respect to instances of 'aster'. One of the popular requirements of PATO is that it continue to support 'absent', so we need to relate statements which use this quality to the 'lacking all parts of type' quality.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.similar_in_magnitude_relative_to
member.summary: "q1 similar_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale."

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.singly_occurring_form_of
member.summary: Description not provided
member.remarks: PATO divides qualities between normal (monadic, singly-occurring) qualities and relational qualities. Relational qualities stand in the 'towards' relation with respect to some additional entity. For example, The sensitivity of an eye towards red light. In some cases we want to represent a quality such as 'protruding' in both monadic and relational branches. We use this relation to link them.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.RelationsOtherTypes.towards

member.remarks: Relation binding a relational quality or disposition to the relevant type of entity.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_accuracy

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_scan_rate
member.summary: Rate in Th/sec for scanning analyzers.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_scan_start_time

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Scan_Function_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Describes the type of mass analysis being performed. Two primary modes are: typical acquisition over a range of masses (Mass Scan), and Selected Ion Detection. member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_scanning_method_OBSOLETE

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_m_z
member.summary: Three-character symbol m/z is used to denote the quantity formed by dividing the mass of an ion in unified atomic mass units by its charge number (regardless of sign). The symbol is written in italicized lower case letters with no spaces. Note 1: The term mass-to-charge-ratio is deprecated. Mass-to-charge ratio has been used for the abscissa of a mass spectrum, although the quantity measured is not the quotient of the ion's mass to its electric charge. The three-character symbol m/z is recommended for the quantity that is the independent variable in a mass spectrum Note 2: The proposed unit thomson (Th) is deprecated.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_state
member.summary: The charge state of the ion, single or multiple and positive or negatively charged.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_peak_intensity
member.summary: Intensity of ions as measured by the height or area of a peak in a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_intensity_unit

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_infusion
member.summary: The continuous flow of solution of a sample into the ionization source.

member.summary: A device that separates carrier gas from gaseous analyte molecules on the basis of diffusivity.

member.summary: Continuous moving surface in the form of a belt which passes through an ion source carrying analyte molecules.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_moving_wire
member.summary: Continuous moving surface in the form of a wire which passes through an ion source carrying analyte molecules.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_open_split
member.summary: A division of flowing stream of liquid into two streams.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_particle_beam
member.summary: Method for generating ions from a solution of an analyte.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_reservoir
member.summary: A sample inlet method involving a reservoir.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_septum
member.summary: A disc composed of a flexible material that seals the entrance to the reservoir. Can also be entrance to the vacuum chamber.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_thermospray_inlet
member.summary: A method for generating gas phase ions from a solution of an analyte by rapid heating of the sample.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_chemical_ionization
member.summary: Chemical ionization that takes place at atmospheric pressure as opposed to the reduced pressure is normally used for chemical ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_chemical_ionization
member.summary: The formation of a new ion by the reaction of a neutral species with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton or other charged species between the reactants. When a positive ion results from chemical ionization the term may be used without qualification. When a negative ion results the term negative ion chemical ionization should be used. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemi-ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Electronic_Ionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electrospray_ionization
member.summary: A process in which ionized species in the gas phase are produced from an analyte-containing solution via highly charged fine droplets, by means of spraying the solution from a narrow-bore needle tip at atmospheric pressure in the presence of a high electric field. When a pressurized gas is used to aid in the formation of a stable spray, the term pneumatically assisted electrospray ionization is used. The term ion spray is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_fast_atom_bombardment_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of neutral atoms having a translational energy of several thousand eV with a sample that is typically dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also secondary ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_matrix_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The formation of gas-phase ions from molecules that are present in a solid or solvent matrix that is irradiated with a pulsed laser. See also laser desorption/ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_negative_ion_mode_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_positive_ion_mode_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_axial_ejection_linear_ion_trap
member.summary: A linear ion trap mass spectrometer where ions are ejected along the axis of the analyzer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_fourier_transform_ion_cyclotron_resonance_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: A mass spectrometer based on the principle of ion cyclotron resonance in which an ion in a magnetic field moves in a circular orbit at a frequency characteristic of its m/z value. Ions are coherently excited to a larger radius orbit using a pulse of radio frequency energy and their image charge is detected on receiver plates as a time domain signal. Fourier transformation of the time domain signal results in a frequency domain signal which is converted to a mass spectrum based in the inverse relationship between frequency and m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_magnetic_sector
member.summary: A device that produces a magnetic field perpendicular to a charged particle beam that deflects the beam to an extent that is proportional to the particle momentum per unit charge. For a monoenergetic beam, the deflection is proportional to m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_quadrupole
member.summary: A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_quadrupole_ion_trap
member.summary: Quadrupole Ion Trap mass analyzer captures the ions in a three dimensional ion trap and then selectively ejects them by varying the RF and DC potentials.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_radial_ejection_linear_ion_trap
member.summary: A linear ion trap mass spectrometer where ions are ejected along the radius of the analyzer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_time_of_flight
member.summary: Instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed acceleration energy.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_baseline
member.summary: An attribute of resolution when recording the detector response in absence of the analyte.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_full_width_at_half_maximum
member.summary: A measure of resolution represented as width of the peak at half peak height.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ten_percent_valley
member.summary: An attribute of resolution when the ratio between adjacent signals is 10% of the signal height.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_constant_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE When resolution is constant with respect to m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_proportional_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE When resolution is proportional with respect to m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A variation of instrument where a selected mass is scanned.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_channeltron
member.summary: A horn-shaped (or cone-shaped) continuous dynode particle multiplier. The ion strikes the inner surface of the device and induces the production of secondary electrons that in turn impinge on the inner surfaces to produce more secondary electrons. This avalanche effect produces an increase in signal in the final measured current pulse.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_conversion_dynode_electron_multiplier
member.summary: A surface that is held at high potential so that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_conversion_dynode_photomultiplier
member.summary: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn generate photons through a phosphorescent screen that are detected by a photomultiplier.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_daly_detector
member.summary: Detector consisting of a conversion dynode, scintillator and photomultiplier. The metal knob at high potential emits secondary electrons when ions impinge on the surface. The secondary electrons are accelerated onto the scintillator that produces light that is then detected by the photomultiplier detector.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_multiplier_tube
member.summary: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_faraday_cup
member.summary: A conducting cup or chamber that intercepts a charged particle beam and is electrically connected to a current measuring device.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_focal_plane_array
member.summary: An array of detectors for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_microchannel_plate_detector
member.summary: A thin plate that contains a closely spaced array of channels that each act as a continuous dynode particle multiplier. A charged particle, fast neutral particle, or photon striking the plate causes a cascade of secondary electrons that ultimately exits the opposite side of the plate.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_multi_collector
member.summary: A detector system commonly used in inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometers.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_photomultiplier
member.summary: A detector for conversion of the ion/electron signal into photon(s) which are then amplified and detected.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_analog_digital_converter
member.summary: Analog-to-digital converter (abbreviated ADC, A/D or A to D) is an electronic integrated circuit (i/c) that converts continuous signals to discrete digital numbers.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_selected_ion_monitoring
member.summary: The operation of a mass spectrometer in which the intensities of several specific m/z values are recorded rather than the entire mass spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_selected_reaction_monitoring
member.summary: Data acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z selected precursor ions recorded via multiple stages of mass spectrometry. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed in time or in space.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_accurate_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An experimentally determined mass that is can be to determine a unique elemental formula. For ions less than 200 u, a measurement with 5 ppm accuracy is sufficient to determine the elemental composition.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_average_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the average mass of each element weighted for its natural isotopic abundance.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_appearance_energy_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The minimum energy that must be imparted to an atom or molecule to produce a specified ion. The term appearance potential is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_base_peak
member.summary: The peak in a mass spectrum that has the greatest intensity. This term may be applied to the spectra of pure substances or mixtures.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_OBSOLETE_charge_number_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The total charge on an ion divided by the electron charge e. OBSOLETED 2009-10-27 since this was viewed as a duplication of 00041 charge state.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_dalton_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A non-SI unit of mass (symbol Da) that is equal to the unified atomic mass unit: 1.660 538 86(28) x 10^-27 kg.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_affinity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The electron affinity of M is the minimum energy required for the process M- ? M + e where M- and M are in their ground rotational, vibrational and electronic states and the electron has zero kinetic energy.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_energy_obsolete_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The potential difference through which electrons are accelerated before they are used to bring about electron ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_exact_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The calculated mass of an ion or molecule containing a single isotope of each atom.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_field_free_region
member.summary: A section of a mass spectrometer in which there are no electric or magnetic fields.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ionization_cross_section_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A measure of the probability that a given ionization process will occur when an atom or molecule interacts with a photon, electron, atom or molecule.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ionization_efficiency_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The ratio of the number of ions formed to the number of electrons, molecules or photons used.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ionization_energy_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The minimum energy required to remove an electron from an atom or molecule to produce a positive ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_isotope_dilution_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A quantitative mass spectrometry technique in which an isotopically enriched compound is used as an internal standard.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_magnetic_deflection
member.summary: The deflection of charged particles in a magnetic field due to a force equal to qvxB where q is the particle charge, v its velocity and B the magnetic field. Magnetic deflection of an ion beam is used for m/z separation in a magnetic sector mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_defect_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The difference between the monoisotopic and nominal mass of a molecule or atom.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_number_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The sum of the protons and neutrons in an atom, molecule or ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_molecular_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The mass of one mole of a molecular substance (6.022 1415(10) x 10^23 molecules).

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_monoisotopic_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the mass of the most abundant isotope of each element.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_molecular_beam_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is introduced into the mass spectrometer as a molecular beam.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_multiphoton_ionization
member.summary: Photoionization of an atom or molecule in which in two or more photons are absorbed.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nitrogen_rule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An organic molecule containing the elements C, H, O, S, P, or halogen has an odd nominal mass if it contains an odd number of nitrogen atoms.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nominal_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the mass of the most abundant isotope of each element rounded to the nearest integer value.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_odd_electron_rule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Odd-electron ions may dissociate to form either odd or even-electron ions, whereas even-electron ions generally form even-electron fragment ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_peak
member.summary: A localized region of relatively large ion signal in a mass spectrum. Although peaks are often associated with particular ions, the terms peak and ion should not be used interchangeably.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_peak_intensity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The height or area of a peak in a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_proton_affinity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The proton affinity of a species M is defined as the negative of the enthalpy change for the reaction M + H+ ->

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_resolving_power_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE In a mass spectrum, the observed mass divided by the difference between two masses that can be separated. The method by which delta m was obtained and the mass at which the measurement was made should be reported.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_total_ion_current_chromatogram
member.summary: Chromatogram obtained by plotting the total ion current detected in each of a series of mass spectra recorded as a function of retention time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_transmission
member.summary: The ratio of the number of ions leaving a region of a mass spectrometer to the number entering that region.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_unified_atomic_mass_unit_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A non-SI unit of mass (u) defined as one twelfth of ^12 C in its ground state and equal to 1.660 538 86(28) x 10^-27 kg.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_accelerator_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometry technique in which atoms extracted from a sample are ionized, accelerated to MeV energies and separated according to their momentum, charge and energy.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_matrix_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the sample target is at atmospheric pressure and the ions formed by the pulsed laser are sampled through a small aperture into the mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_ionization
member.summary: Any ionization process in which ions are formed in the gas phase at atmospheric pressure.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Atmostpheric_Pressure_Photoionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_blackbody_infrared_radiative_dissociation
member.summary: A special case of infrared multiphoton dissociation wherein excitation of the reactant ion is caused by absorption of infrared photons radiating from heated blackbody surroundings, which are usually the walls of a vacuum chamber. See also infrared multiphoton dissociation.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_remote_fragmentation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A fragmentation of an even-electron ion in which the cleaved bond is not adjacent to the apparent charge site.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_consecutive_reaction_monitoring_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE MSn experiment with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_stripping
member.summary: The reaction of a positive ion with an atom or molecule that results in the removal of one or more electrons from the ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_delayed_extraction
member.summary: The application of the accelerating voltage pulse after a time delay in desorption ionization from a surface. The extraction delay can produce energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The formation of ions from a solid or liquid material after the rapid vaporization of that sample.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_direct_insertion_probe
member.summary: A device for introducing a solid or liquid sample into a mass spectrometer ion source for desorption ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_direct_liquid_introduction
member.summary: The delivery of a liquid sample into a mass spectrometer for spray or desorption ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_capture_dissociation
member.summary: A process in which a multiply protonated molecules interacts with a low energy electrons. Capture of the electron leads the liberation of energy and a reduction in charge state of the ion with the production of the (M + nH) (n-1)+ odd electron ion, which readily fragments.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_even_electron_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion containing no unpaired electrons in its ground electronic state, e.g. CH3+ in its ground state.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_induced_excitation_in_organics_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with an electron in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_multiplier
member.summary: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons. The secondary electrons are then accelerated to other electrodes or parts of a continuous electrode to produce further secondary electrons.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electrostatic_energy_analyzer
member.summary: A device consisting of conducting parallel plates, concentric cylinders or concentric spheres that separates charged particles according to their kinetic energy by means of an electric field that is constant in time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_flowing_afterglow
member.summary: An ion source immersed in a flow of helium or other inert buffer gas that carries the ions through a meter-long reactor at pressures around 100 Pa.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_high_field_asymmetric_waveform_ion_mobility_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The separation of ions between two concentric cylindrical electrodes due to application of a high voltage asymmetric waveform whereby ions migrate towards one of the two electrodes depending on the ratio of the high- to low-field mobility of the ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_field_desorption
member.summary: The formation of gas-phase ions from a material deposited on a solid surface in the presence of a high electric field. Because this process may encompass ionization by field ionization or other mechanisms, it is not recommended as a synonym for field desorption ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_field_ionization
member.summary: The removal of electrons from any species by interaction with a high electric field.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_glow_discharge_ionization
member.summary: The formation of ions in the gas phase and from solid samples at the cathode by application of a voltage to a low pressure gas.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_kinetic_energy_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A method of analysis in which a beam of ions is separated according to the ratio of its translational energy to charge.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_mobility_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The separation of ions according to their velocity through a buffer gas under the influence of an electric field.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_infrared_multiphoton_dissociation
member.summary: Multiphoton ionization where the reactant ion dissociates as a result of the absorption of multiple infrared photons.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_isotope_ratio_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The measurement of the relative quantity of the different isotopes of an element in a material with a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_trap
member.summary: A device for spatially confining ions using electric and magnetic fields alone or in combination.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_kinetic_energy_release_distribution_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Distribution of values of translational kinetic energy release for an ensemble of metastable ions undergoing a specific dissociation reaction.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Laser_Desorption_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The formation of ions through the interaction of a laser with a material or with gas-phase ions or molecules.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_analyzed_ion_kinetic_energy_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Spectra that are obtained from a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector in reverse geometry. The accelerating voltage, V, and the magnetic sector field, B, are set at fixed values to select the precursor ions, which are then allowed to dissociate or to react in a field free region between the two sectors. The kinetic energy product ions of m/z selected precursor ions is analyzed by scanning the electric sector field, E. The width of the product ion spectrum peaks is related to the kinetic energy release distribution (KERD) for the dissociation process.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The branch of science that deals with all aspects of mass spectrometers and the results obtained with these instruments.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometry_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The acquisition, study and spectra of the electrically charged products or precursors of a m/z selected ion or ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_multiple_stage_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Multiple stages of precursor ion m/z selection followed by product ion detection for successive progeny ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Negative_Ion_chemical_ionization
member.summary: Chemical ionization that results in the formation of negative ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_neutralization_reionization_mass_spectrometry
member.summary: With this technique, m/z selected ions form neutrals by charge transfer to a collision gas or by dissociation. The neutrals are separated from the remaining ions and ionized in collisions with a second gas. This method is used to investigate reaction intermediates and other unstable species.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_photoionization
member.summary: The ionization of an atom or molecule by a photon, written M + h? ? M^+ + e. The term photon impact is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_pyrolysis_mass_spectrometry
member.summary: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is heated to the point of decomposition and the gaseous decomposition products are introduced into the ion source.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_collision_quadrupole
member.summary: A transmission quadrupole to which an oscillating potential is applied so as to focus a beam of ions through a collision gas with no m/z separation.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_resonance_enhanced_multiphoton_ionization
member.summary: Multiphoton ionization in which the ionization cross section is significantly enhanced because the energy of the incident photons is resonant with an intermediate excited state of the neutral species.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_residual_gas_analyzer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer used to measure the composition and pressure of gasses in an evacuated chamber.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_surface_enhanced_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The formation of ionized species in the gas phase from analytes deposited on a particular surface substrate which is irradiated with a laser beam of which wavelength is absorbed by the surface. See also desorption/ionization on silicon and laser desorption/ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_surface_enhanced_neat_desorption
member.summary: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the matrix is covalently linked to the target surface.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_suface_ionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_selected_ion_flow_tube
member.summary: A device in which m/z selected ions are entrained in an inert carrier gas and undergo ion-molecule reactions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_sustained_off_resonance_irradiation
member.summary: A technique associated with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR) mass spectrometry to carry out ion/neutral reactions such as low-energy collision-induced dissociation. A radio-frequency electric field of slightly off-resonance to the cyclotron frequency of the reactant ion cyclically accelerates and decelerates the reactant ion that is confined in the Penning ion trap. The ion's orbit does not exceed the dimensions of ion trap while the ion undergoes an ion/neutral species process that produces a high average translational energy for an extended time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Spark_Source_Mass_Spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Mass spectrometry using spark ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_stored_waveform_inverse_fourier_transform
member.summary: A technique to create excitation waveforms for ions in FT-ICR mass spectrometer or Paul ion trap. An excitation waveform in the time-domain is generated by taking the inverse Fourier transform of an appropriate frequency-domain programmed excitation spectrum, in which the resonance frequencies of ions to be excited are included. This technique may be used for selection of precursor ions in MS2 experiments.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_total_ion_current
member.summary: The sum of all the separate ion currents carried by the ions of different m/z contributing to a complete mass spectrum or in a specified m/z range of a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_time_lag_focusing
member.summary: Energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer that is accomplished by introducing a time delay between the formation of the ions and the application of the accelerating voltage pulse.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_time_of_flight_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed kinetic energy.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_cyclotron
member.summary: A device that uses an oscillating electric field and magnetic field to accelerate charged particles.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_double_focusing_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that uses a magnetic sector for m/z focusing and an electric sector for energy focusing of an ion beam.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_hybrid_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that combines m/z analyzers of different types to perform tandem mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_linear_ion_trap
member.summary: A two dimensional Paul ion trap in which ions are confined in the axial dimension by means of an electric field at the ends of the trap.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_spectrograph_obsolete_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An instrument that separates a beam of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio in which the ions are directed onto a focal plane detector such as a photographic plate.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An instrument that measures the mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundances of ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_spectrum
member.summary: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z).

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mattauch_herzog_geometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/(4 ?(2)) radians in a radial electric field is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/2 radians.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nier_johnson_geometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/2 radians in a radial electric field analyzer is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/3 radians.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_paul_ion_trap_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A device that permits the trapping of ions by means of an alternating current voltage. The ejection of ions with a m/z less than a prescribed value and retention of those with higher mass depends on the application of radio frequency voltages between a ring electrode and two end-cap electrodes to confine the ions in a circular path. The choice of these voltages determines the m/z below which ions are ejected.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_prolate_traochoidal_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer in which the ions of different m/z are separated by means of crossed electric and magnetic fields in such a way that the selected ions follow a prolate trochoidal path.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_quistor_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An abbreviation of quadrupole ion storage trap. This term is synonymous with Paul Ion Trap. If so then add a synonym to paul and obsolete this term.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_reflectron
member.summary: A time-of-flight mass spectrometer that uses a static electric field to reverse the direction of travel of the ions entering it. A reflectron improves mass resolution by assuring that ions of the same m/z but different kinetic energy arrive at the detector at the same time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_sector_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer consisting of one or more magnetic sectors for m/z selection in a beam of ions. Such instruments may also have one or more electric sectors for energy selection.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_tandem_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer designed for mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_transmission_quadrupole_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_accelerating_voltage
member.summary: The electrical potential used to impart kinetic energy to ions in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_cyclotron_motion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The circular motion of a charged particle moving at velocity v in a magnetic field B that results from the force qvB.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_dynamic_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer in which m/z separation using one or more electric fields that vary with time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_einzel_lens
member.summary: Three element charged particle lens in which the first and third elements are held at the same voltage. Such a lens produces focusing without changing the translational energy of the particle.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electric_field_strength
member.summary: The magnitude of the force per unit charge at a given point in space.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_first_stability_region
member.summary: The region of a Mathieu stability diagram closest to the origin. Ions within this region can traverse the full length of a transmission quadrupole.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_fringing_field
member.summary: The electric or magnetic field that extends from the edge of a sector, lens or other ion optics element.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_kinetic_energy_analyzer
member.summary: A device for measuring the kinetic energy of charged particles using a retarding field, time-of-flight, or the extent of deflection in an electric or magnetic field.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_limit_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The m/z value above which ions cannot be detected in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_scan_m_z_range__OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The limit of m/z over which a mass spectrometer can detect ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_selective_axial_ejection_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The use of mass selective instability to eject ions of selected m/z values from an ion trap.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_selective_instability_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A method for selective ejection of ions according to their m/z value in an ion trap.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mathieu_stability_diagram_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A graphical representation expressed in terms of reduced coordinates that describes charged particle motion in a quadrupole mass filter or quadrupole ion trap mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_orthogonal_extraction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The pulsed acceleration of ions perpendicular to their direction of travel into a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. Ions may be extracted from a directional ion source, drift tube or m/z separation stage.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_resonance_ion_ejection_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mode of ion ejection in a quadrupole ion trap that relies on a auxiliary radio frequency voltage that is applied to the end-cap electrodes. The voltage is tuned to the secular frequency of a particular ion to eject it.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_space_charge_effect
member.summary: The mutual repulsion of particles of like charge that limits the current in a charged-particle beam and causes beams or packets of charged particles to expand radially over time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_static_field
member.summary: An electric or magnetic field that does not change in time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_2E_Mass_Spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrum obtained by setting the electric sector field E to twice the value required to transmit the main ion-beam thereby allowing ions with a kinetic energy-to-charge ratio twice that of the main ion-beam to be transmitted. Product ions resulting from partial charge transfer reactions such as m^2+ + N ? m^+ + N^+ that occur in a collision cell (containing a gas, N) located in a field-free region preceding a magnetic and electric sector combination are detected. When the magnetic sector field B is scanned, a mass spectrum of singly charged product ions of doubly charged precursor ions is obtained.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_mass_spectrum
member.summary: The measurement of the relative abundance of ions that result from a charge inversion reaction as a function of m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z decrement.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_spectrum
member.summary: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_spectrum
member.summary: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_consecutive_reaction_monitoring_OBSOLETE1
member.summary: OBSOLETE A type of MS2 experiments with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_e_2_mass_spectrum
member.summary: A mass spectrum obtained using a sector mass spectrometer in which the electric sector field E is set to half the value required to transmit the main ion-beam. This spectrum records the signal from doubly charged product ions of charge-stripping reactions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_linked_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A scan in an instrument with two or more m/z analysers or in a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector and one electric sector. Two or more of the analyzers are scanned simultaneously so as to preserve a predetermined relationship between scan parameters to produce a product ion, precursor ion or constant neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_linked_scan_at_constant_b_e_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A linked scan at constant B/E may be performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector. The magnetic field B and the electric field E are scanned simultaneously while the accelerating voltage V is held constant, so as to maintain the ratio of the two fields constant. This linked scan may record a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_E2_V_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector. The electric sector field, E, and the accelerating voltage, V, are scanned simultaneously, so as to maintain the ratio E2/V at a constant value. This linked scan recordss a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region (FFR) preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B2_E_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed and the magnetic field, B, and the electric field, E, are scanned simultaneously so as to maintain the ratio B2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a precursor ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in the field free region preceding the two sectors. The term B2/E linked scan is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B_1__E_E0___1_2___E_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector placed in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed while scanning the magnetic field, B, and electric field, E, simultaneously, so as to maintain the quantity B

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Time_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in a single m/z analyzer (such as a Paul Ion Trap or FTMS) in discreet steps over time. Ions in a specific m/z range are selected, dissociated, and the product ions analyzed sequentially in time.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Space_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in m/z analyzers separated in space. Specific m/z separation functions are designed such that in one section of the instrument ions are selected, dissociated in an intermediate region, and the product ions are then transmitted to another analyser for m/z separation and data acquisition.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_neutral_loss
member.summary: The loss of an uncharged species during a rearrangement process. The value slot holds the molecular formula in Hill notation of the neutral loss molecule, see PMID: 21182243. This term must be used in conjunction with a child of the term MS:1002307 (fragmentation ion type).

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Serial product ions from dissociation of selected precursor ions where n refers to the number of stages of dissociation. The term granddaughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The specific scan functions or processes that record the appropriate generation of product ion or ions of any m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The mass spectrum recorded from any mass spectrometer in which the appropriate scan function can be set to record the appropriate generation product ion or ions of m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_precursor_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion that reacts to form particular product ions. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation, ion/molecule reaction, isomerization, or change in charge state. The term parent ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_precursor_ion_spectrum
member.summary: Spectrum generated by scanning precursor m/z while monitoring a fixed product m/z.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_product_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed as the product of a reaction involving a particular precursor ion. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation to form fragment ions, an ion/molecule reaction, or simply involve a change in the number of charges. The term fragment ion is deprecated. The term daughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A mass spectrum recorded from any spectrometer in which the appropriate m/z separation scan function is set to record the product ion or ions of selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_progeny_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_array_detector
member.summary: Detector comprising several ion collection elements, arranged in a line or grid where each element is an individual detector.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_conversion_dynode
member.summary: A surface that is held at high potential such that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_dynode
member.summary: One of a series of electrodes in a photomultiplier tube. Such an arrangement is able to amplify the current emitted by the photocathode.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_focal_plane_collector
member.summary: A detector for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_to_photon_detector
member.summary: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn strike a phosphor and the resulting photons are detected by a photomultiplier.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_point_collector
member.summary: A detector in which the ion beam is focused onto a point and the individual ions arrive sequentially.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_postacceleration_detector
member.summary: A detector in which the charged particles are accelerated to a high velocity and impinge on a conversion dynode, emitting secondary electrons. The electrons are accelerated onto a phosphor screen, which emits photons that are in turn detected using a photomultiplier or other photon detector.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_secondary_electron_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Electrons that are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms, ions or photons. WAS IN DETECTOR TYPE. Where should it go.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_adduct_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Ion formed by the interaction of an ion with one or more atoms or molecules to form an ion containing all the constituent atoms of the precursor ion as well as the additional atoms from the associated atoms or molecules.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_aromatic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A planar cyclic ion that obeys the Hueckel (4n + 2) rule where n is a positive integer representing the number of conjugated Pi electrons. Charge delocalization leads to greater stability compared to a hypothetical localized structure.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_analog_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Ions that have similar chemical valence, for example the acetyl cation CH3-CO+ and the thioacetyl cation CH3-CS+.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_anti_aromatic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A planar cyclic ion with 4n ? electrons and is therefore not aromatic.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_cationized_molecule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed by the association of a cation with a neutral molecule, M, for example

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_cluster_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed by a multi-component atomic or molecular assembly of one or more ions with atoms or molecules, such as

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Conventional_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin are both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms, as opposed to the spatially separate electronic configuration of distonic ions. The radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+, in which the charge and spin sites are formally located at the O atom is an example of a conventional ion, whereas .CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_diagnostic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A product ion whose formation reveals structural or compositional information of its precursor. For instance, the phenyl cation in an electron ionization mass spectrum is a diagnostic ion for benzene and derivatives.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_dimeric_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed by ionization of a dimer or by the association of an ion with its neutral counterpart such as

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_distonic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin cannot be both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms as it can be with a conventional ion. For example, CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion whereas the radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+ is a conventional ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_enium_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A positively charged lower-valency ion of the nonmetallic elements. The methenium ion is CH3+. Other examples are the oxenium, sulfenium, nitrenium, phosphenium, and halenium ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_fragment_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A product ion that results from the dissociation of a precursor ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion__OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An atomic or molecular species having a net positive or negative electric charge.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Isotopologue_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion that differs only in the isotopic composition of one or more of its constituent atoms. For example CH4+ and CH3D+ or 10BF3 and 11BF3. The term isotopologue is a contraction of isotopic homologue.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_Isotopomeric_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Isomeric ion having the same numbers of each isotopic atom but differing in their positions. Isotopomeric ions can be either configurational isomers in which two atomic isotopes exchange positions or isotopic stereoisomers. The term isotopomer is a shortening of isotopic isomer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_metastable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion that is formed with internal energy higher than the threshold for dissociation but with a lifetime great enough to allow it to exit the ion source and enter the mass spectrometer where it dissociates before detection.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_molecular_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed by the removal of one or more electrons to form a positive ion or the addition off one or more electrons to form a negative ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_negative_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An atomic or molecular species having a net negative electric charge.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_non_classical_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Hyper-coordinated carbonium ion such as the penta-coordinated norbornyl cation. Note: Tri-coordinated carbenium ions are termed classical ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_onium_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A positively charged hypervalent ion of the nonmetallic elements. Examples are the methonium ion CH5+, the hydrogenonium ion H3+ and the hydronium ion H3O+. Other examples are the carbonium, oxonium, sulfonium, nitronium, diazonium, phosphonium, and halonium ions. Onium ions are not limited to monopositive ions; multiply-charged onium ions exist such as the gitonic (proximal) oxonium dication H4O2+ and the distonic oxonium dication H2O+-CH2-CH2-OH2+.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_principal_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Most abundant ion of an isotope cluster, such as the 11B79Br2 81Br+ ion of m/z 250 of the cluster of isotopologue molecular ions of BBr3. The term principal ion has also been used to describe ions that have been artificially isotopically enriched in one or more positions such as CH3 13CH3+ or CH2D2 +, but those are best defined as isotopologue ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_positive_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An atomic or molecular species having a net positive electric charge.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_protonated_molecule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion formed by interaction of a neutral molecule with a proton and represented by the symbol

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_radical_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion, either a cation or anion, containing unpaired electrons in its ground state. The unpaired electron is denoted by a superscript dot alongside the superscript symbol for charge, such as for the molecular ion of a molecule M, that is, M+. Radical ions with more than one charge and/or more than one unpaired electron are denoted such as M(2+)(2). Unless the positions of the unpaired electron and charge can be associated with specific atoms, superscript charge designation should be placed before the superscript dot designation.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_reference_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A stable ion whose structure is known with certainty. These ions are usually formed by direct ionization of a neutral molecule of known structure and are used to verify by comparison the structure of an unknown ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_stable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion with internal energy sufficiently low that it does not rearrange or dissociate prior to detection in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_unstable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An ion with sufficient energy to dissociate within the ion source.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_adiabatic_ionization
member.summary: A process whereby an electron is removed from an atom, ion, or molecule to produce an ion in its lowest energy state.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_associative_ionization
member.summary: An ionization process in which two excited atoms or molecules react to form a single positive ion and an electron.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_photoionization
member.summary: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_autodetachment
member.summary: The formation of a neutral when a negative ion in a discrete state with an energy greater than the detachment threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_autoionization
member.summary: The formation of an ion when an atom or molecule in a discrete state with an energy greater than the ionization threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_exchange_ionization
member.summary: The interaction of an ion with an atom or molecule in which the charge on the ion is transferred to the neutral without the dissociation of either. Synonymous with charge transfer ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_chemi_ionization
member.summary: The reaction of a neutral molecule with an internally excited molecule to form an ion. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemical ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_desorption_ionization_on_silicon
member.summary: The formation of ions by laser desorption ionization of a sample deposited on a porous silicon surface.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_dissociative_ionization
member.summary: The reaction of a gas-phase molecule that results in its decomposition to form products, one of which is an ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_electron_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_desolvation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The removal of solvent molecules clustered around a gas-phase ion by means of heating and/or collisions with gas molecules.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_pair_formation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of a molecule to form both a positive ion and negative ion fragment among the products.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ionization_efficiency
member.summary: The ratio of the number of ions formed to the number of electrons, molecules or photons used.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The formation of gas-phase ions by the interaction of a pulsed laser with a solid or liquid material.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_liquid_secondary_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of ions with a sample that is dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also fast atom bombardment and secondary ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_membrane_inlet
member.summary: A semi-permeable membrane separator that permits the passage of gas sample directly to the mass spectrometer ion source.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_microelectrospray
member.summary: Electrospray ionization at a solvent flow rate of 300-800 nL/min where the flow is a result of a mechanical pump. See nanoelectrospray.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_nanoelectrospray
member.summary: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_penning_ionization
member.summary: Ionization that occurs through the interaction of two or more neutral gaseous species, at least one of which is internally excited.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_plasma_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_pre_ionization_state_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An electronic state capable of undergoing auto-Ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_secondary_ionization
member.summary: The process in which ions are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms or ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_soft_ionization
member.summary: The formation of gas-phase ions without extensive fragmentation.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_spark_ionization
member.summary: The formation of ions from a solid material by an intermittent electrical discharge.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_surface_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: The formation of gas-phase ions from molecules that are deposited on a particular surface substrate that is irradiated with a pulsed laser. See also matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_surface_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_thermal_ionization
member.summary: The ionization of a neutral species through contact with a high temperature surface.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_vertical_ionization
member.summary: A process in which an electron is removed from or added to a molecule without a change in the positions of the atoms. The resulting ion is typically in an excited vibrational state.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_association_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the reactants combine to form a single ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_alpha_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at the atom adjacent to the atom at the apparent charge site and an atom removed from the aparent charge site by two bonds.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_beta_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at an atom removed from the apparent charge site atom by two bonds and an atom adjacent to that atom and removed from the aparent charge site by three bonds.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_buffer_gas
member.summary: An inert gas used for collisional deactivation of internally excited ions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_induced_fragmentation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Fragmentation of an odd electron ion in which the cleaved bond is adjacent to the apparent charge site. Synonymous with charge mediated fragmentation.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the charge on the product ion is reversed in sign with respect to the reactant ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_permutation_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral species with a resulting change in the magnitude or sign of the charge on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_stripping_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Reaction of a positive ion with a neutral species in which the positive charge on the product ion is greater than that on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_charge_transfer_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some or all of the charge of the reactant ion is transferred to the neutral species.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_collisional_excitation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_collision_gas
member.summary: An inert gas used for collisional excitation. The term target gas is not recommended.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_heterolytic_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Fragmentation of a molecule or ion in which both electrons forming the single bond that is broken remain on one of the atoms that were originally bonded. This term is synonymous with heterolysis.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_high_energy_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Collision-induced dissociation process wherein the projectile ion has laboratory-frame translational energy higher than 1 keV.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_beam_type_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: A collision-induced dissociation process that occurs in a beam-type collision cell.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_homolytic_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Fragmentation of an odd electron ion that results from one of a pair of electrons that form a bond between two atoms moving to form a pair with the odd electron on the atom at the apparent charge site. Fragmentation results in the formation of an even electron ion and a radical. This reaction involves the movement of a single electron and is symbolized by a single-barbed arrow. Synonymous with Homolysis.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_hydrogen_deuterium_exchange_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Exchange of hydrogen atoms with deuterium atoms in a molecule or pre-formed ion in solution prior to introduction into a mass spectrometer, or by reaction of an ion with a deuterated collision gas inside a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_energy_loss_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function their loss of translational energy in reactions with neutral species.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ionizing_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which one or more electrons are removed from either the ion or neutral.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_molecule_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with a neutral molecule. The term ion-molecule reaction is not recommended because the hyphen suggests a single species that is that is both an ion and a molecule.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_complex_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A particular type of transition state that lies between precursor and product ions on the reaction coordinate of some ion reactions.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A process wherein a charged species interacts with a neutral reactant to produce either chemically different species or changes in the internal energy of one or both of the reactants.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_exchange_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE In this reaction an association reaction is accompanied by the subsequent or simultaneous liberation of a different neutral species as a product.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_kinetic_method_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE An approach to determination of ion thermodynamic quantities by a bracketing procedure in which the relative probabilities of competing ion fragmentations are measured via the relative abundances of the reaction products. The extended kinetic method takes the associated entropy changes into account.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_low_energy_collisions_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A collision between an ion and neutral species with translational energy approximately 1000 eV or lower.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_low_energy_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: A collision-induced dissociation process wherein the precursor ion has the translational energy lower than approximately 1000 eV. This process typically requires multiple collisions and the collisional excitation is cumulative.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_McLafferty_Rearrangement_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A dissociation reaction triggered by transfer of a hydrogen atom via a 6-member transition state to the formal radical/charge site from a carbon atom four atoms removed from the charge/radical site (the gamma-carbon); subsequent rearrangement of electron density leads to expulsion of an olefin molecule. This term was originally applied to ketone ions where the charge/radical site is the carbonyl oxygen, but it is now more widely applied.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_photodissociation
member.summary: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_partial_charge_transfer_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some but not all of the ion charge is transferred to the neutral.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Chemical transformation involving an ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_superelastic_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Collision in which the translational energy of the fast-moving collision partner is increased at the expense of internal energy of one or both collision partners.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_surface_induced_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE A process wherein a reactant ion interacts with a surface to produce either chemically different species or a change in the internal energy of the reactant ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_unimolecular_dissociation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Fragmentation reaction in which the molecularity is treated as one, irrespective of whether the dissociative state is that of a metastable ion produced in the ion source or results from collisional excitation of a stable ion.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_scan
member.summary: Function or process of the mass spectrometer where it records a spectrum.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_spectrum
member.summary: A mass spectrum is an intensity vs m/z (mass-to-charge ratio) plot representing a chemical analysis.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_mass_analyzer_type
member.summary: Mass analyzer separates the ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_m_z_Separation_Method_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Mass/charge separation Method.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_sequential_m_z_separation_method_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE Sequential m/z separation method.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_fast_ion_bombardment
member.summary: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of ions having a translational energy of several thousand eV with a solid sample.

member.summary: Finnigan LTQ MS.

member.summary: Finnigan LTQ FT MS.

member.summary: Finnigan LXQ MS.

member.summary: Terms used to describe the Analyzer.

member.summary: Terms used to describe types of data processing.

member.summary: The device that detects ions.

member.summary: OBSOLETE Additional terms to describe the instrument as outlined in the mass spec doc, Appendix 1, section 1.5.

member.name: F:PSI_Interface.CV.CV.CVID.MS_ion_selection_attribute
member.summary: Ion selection properties that are associated with a value.

member.summary: Terms to describe the precursor activation.

member.summary: Terms to describe the sample.

member.summary: Terms to describe the source.

member.summary: OBSOLETE Terms used to describe the spectrum.

member.summary: OBSOLETE Terms to describe units.
